x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><ol style=3D"margin=
:0;color:#000000;font-size:16px;line-height:30px;margin-top:0;margin-bottom=
:0;list-style-type:decimal"><li><i>Charter-Disney deal, redux</i>: When Cha=
rter closed its contentious deal with Disney, last September, the distribut=
or received a <i>ton</i> of praise for convincing the executives in Burbank=
 to allow their ad-supported apps=E2=80=94Disney+ in Spectrum TV Select, an=
d ESPN+ in Spectrum TV Select Plus=E2=80=94on to the company=E2=80=99s syst=
ems. But several sources have told me that the Disney streaming products ha=
ve performed poorly so far for Charter, with take rate for both apps way do=
wn in the single digits. Sure, it=E2=80=99s early days, and the very notion=
 of cable operators offering streaming apps is likely still unfamiliar to s=
ubscribers. And yes, Charter hasn=E2=80=99t really marketed them to consume=
rs, though I expect those efforts to ramp up when
it adds more services, like Paramount+ (later this year) and ESPN Flagship =
(next year). But it=E2=80=99s also possible that streaming is just simply <=
i>not</i> a good substitute for the cable bundle, especially among older su=
bscribers. If these numbers stay low, they have the potential to swing nego=
tiating leverage in carriage battles with distributors back to the programm=
ers. </li><br/><li><i>Roku=E2=80=99s MLB Season</i>: This morning, I caught=
 up with two Roku executives to talk about their package of Sunday morning =
MLB games=E2=80=94part of the three-year, $30 million deal that the company=
 signed in May=E2=80=94and what that means for future dealflow. Here=E2=80=
=99s a brief excerpt of our conversation, lightly edited and condensed.<br/=
><br/><b><i>John Ourand</i>: How should other leagues view this MLB deal?</=
b><br/><br/><i>Joe Franzetta, head of sports for Roku Media</i>: There are =
always going to be selective opportunities that make sense for us to consid=
er. Live packages make sense either because
we think there=E2=80=99s higher viewer demand, or because the opportunity c=
an drive new viewers to our platform. We=E2=80=99re an ad-supported platfor=
m, so we have sponsor and advertiser demand and we can create unique packag=
es.<br/><br/><i>David Eilenberg, head of content Roku Media</i>: This is th=
e oldest lesson in the history of TV, but dayparting [the practice of break=
ing the schedule into segments, and tailoring programming to each segment] =
is really important. The Sunday morning window has been a real virtue of th=
e MLB package as well.<br/><br/><b>How did the deal come about?</b><br/><br=
/><i>Franzetta</i>: We were talking initially about building an MLB Zone. W=
e already had NFL Zone and NBA Zone launched, and it was a natural conversa=
tion to have with MLB. They introduced the concept of the package of games,=
 which was a natural fit. So the partnership went from inception to executi=
on in a relatively short period of time. Kudos to those guys for seeing the=
 vision of this overall
comprehensive one-stop shop.<br/><br/>People tend to focus on the games. Bu=
t from our perspective, it=E2=80=99s important to think about it in the con=
text of our MLB Zone, which is part of our sports zone. MLB Zone has every =
game integrated into it. We have clips and highlights from every single gam=
e. We have other V.O.D. content that MLB provides. <br/><br/><b>What=E2=80=
=99s been the most memorable game so far?</b><br/><br/><i>Franzetta</i>: Wh=
en you get a rabid fan base, you see things really pop. We had a Phillies-D=
iamondback game, and the Phillies fans showed up in strong numbers. And so =
that was kind of an <i>aha</i> moment in terms of the way it brings new fan=
s to Roku.</li><br/><li><i>The Copa disaster</i>: One of the major <u><a hr=
ef=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ=
0dRdU5iT3F2a0dSR1dwUzlZNzhXWT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9zcG9y=
dHMvc29jY2VyL2FyZ2VudGluYS1jb2xvbWJpYS1jb3BhLWFtZXJpY2EtMjAyNC1oYXJkLXJvY2s=
tc3RhZGl1bS0xYzY5NTJhZD9tb2Q9aHBfZmVhdHN0X3BvczNcdTAwMjZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249VG=
hlK1ZhcnNpdHkrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjg3JTJGMTUlMkYyNCUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9jb250Z=
W50PVRoZStWYXJzaXR5Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4NiUyRjYlMkYyNCUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9t=
ZWRpdW09ZW1haWxfYWN0aW9uXHUwMDI2dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jdXN0b21lci5pb1x1MDAyNnV0bV9=
0ZXJtPWY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImludGVybmFsIjoiZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIi=
wibGlua19pZCI6OTU5OTM2fQ/1e9f64759f43b6e7b611b98a40483466d39d92c15cd3cc0384=
4c2b729d1d40be" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bol=
d" class=3D"sdf">storylines</a></u> <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e=
/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dRdU5iT3F2a0dSR1dwUzlZNzhXWT0i=
LCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvZGU3NGRjYzAtNTRjNy00NDI4LTh=
hZWQtMWFlOTZmZDkyOGE4P3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1UaGUrVmFyc2l0eSstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKy=
UyODclMkYxNSUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9VGhlK1ZhcnNpdHkrLStTVUJTQ1JJQ=
kVSUyslMjg2JTJGNiUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1=
dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiw=
iaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjo5NTk5Mzd9/20bd10f5e=
a4d77dff0134da11cfb128c4c180734a4aedb47d40fcc9a7d115d8d" style=3D"color:#d4=
0000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">emerging</a></u> =
from yesterday=E2=80=99s drama-filled Copa America finals, where kickoff wa=
s delayed by more than an hour after thousands of ticketless fans tried to =
sneak into the stadium, was whether the North American nations can manage t=
he World Cup in two years. I contacted a couple of sports business executiv=
es, and they placed blame squarely on the shoulders of the tournament=E2=80=
=99s organizer, CONMEBOL, particularly with regard to the security breach a=
t Miami=E2=80=99s Hard Rock Stadium. <br/><br/>One executive was especially=
 surprised
that CONMEBOL didn=E2=80=99t set up a security perimeter to keep ticketless=
 fans away from the stadium. =E2=80=9CFIFA will set up those perimeters,=E2=
=80=9D this person told me. =E2=80=9CThat Miami stadium hosts Super Bowls; =
it knows how to handle big events.=E2=80=9D There were also problems with t=
he telecast. The World Feed=E2=80=94the subject of constant complaints thro=
ughout the tournament=E2=80=94actually went down <i>during the game</i>, fo=
rcing Fox to rely on a secondary feed. Plus, my social channels were filled=
 with complaints about the broadcast=E2=80=99s sound quality=E2=80=A6<br/><=
br/></li><li><i>What to do with the MLB Draft</i>: Sure, MLB should be cong=
ratulated for turning its annual draft into a <i>thing</i>=E2=80=94albeit a=
 much, much smaller <i>thing</i> than the NFL and the NBA=E2=80=99s own ama=
teur selection events. On Sunday night, the league hosted 2,000 fans in the=
 117-year-old Cowtown Coliseum in Fort Worth. ESPN and MLB Network provided=
 live national coverage, which should draw around 700,000 viewers combined,=
 if
previous years are any indication. The league also ensured that it didn=E2=
=80=99t create any internal competition for the draft in the form of live g=
ames or exhibitions.<br/><br/>Even still, the draft faded into the woodwork=
=E2=80=94one more event during a packed All-Star Game weekend. Some are now=
 suggesting that the league should implement even more changes to put the e=
vent on a steeper growth trajectory. The proposal that makes the most sense=
 to me is moving the draft to Omaha, and holding the draft in conjunction w=
ith the College World Series. After all, college baseball fans will be more=
 likely to follow the draft than All-Star week attendees. (Tellingly, only =
six draftees attended on Sunday.) For now, MLB is not considering this move=
, but it <i>should</i>. <br/><br/></li><li><i>The sports doc trend continue=
s</i>: I had a meeting with a streaming executive in Dallas, and we laughed=
 about how often the executive gets pitched on all-access <i>Drive to Survi=
ve</i>-style documentaries.
I keep waiting for the doc market to crash, and yet this genre appears to b=
e as popular as ever. To wit: <i>Receiver</i>, the NFL Films/Omaha Producti=
ons unofficial spinoff of <i>Quarterback</i>, has been the top Netflix show=
 in the U.S. for four consecutive days. <i>America=E2=80=99s Sweethearts</i=
