x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Ever since NBC stra=
tegically <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ=
4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dRdU5iT3F2a0dSR1dwUzlZNzhXWT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cud3NqLmNvbS9idXNpbmVzcy9tZWRpYS9uYmMtcHJlcGFyZXMtcm91Z2hseS0yLTUtYmlsbGlvb=
i1hLXllYXItb2ZmZXItdG8tc3RlYWwtbmJhLXJpZ2h0cy1hd2F5LWZyb20tdG50LWU2ZTE0ZWVi=
P3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1UaGUrVmFyc2l0eSstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODclMkYxNSUyRjI0JTI=
5XHUwMDI2dXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9VGhlK1ZhcnNpdHkrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjg2JTJGNiUyRj=
I0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3Rvb=
WVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2=
MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjo5NTk5MzJ9/c635fd53810fc49a9488703652f4c1=
d1f0aa9331305b9173959f65c967def0bf" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:=
none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">leaked</a></u> its <i>$2.5 billion-a-y=
ear </i>bid for the NBA=E2=80=99s coveted =E2=80=9CB=E2=80=9D package, back=
 in June, the sports media industry has waited deliberately to see how Warn=
er Bros. Discovery would reciprocate. C.E.O. <b>David Zaslav</b>, of course=
, had previously and famously pooh-poohed the exorbitant cost of NBA rights=
, and even suggested that his conglomerate could survive without them. Mean=
while, the <i>Journal</i>=E2=80=99s report of
the NBC bid tested this hypothesis, sending WBD=E2=80=99s stock further dow=
nward and unleashing a chain reaction of derivative events including, but n=
ot limited to, public mourning about the potential finale of the beloved <i=
>Inside the NBA</i>, <b>Charles Barkley</b>=E2=80=99s announced forthcoming=
 retirement from broadcasting, Zaz=E2=80=99s courtside support of the Knick=
s=E2=80=99 playoff run, and=E2=80=94lo and behold=E2=80=94his suggestion th=
at his lawyers would be reviewing their contract to deploy the company=E2=
=80=99s vaunted <i>matching rights</i>.<br/><br/>The NBA rights deal, which=
 was negotiated interminably, will <i>finally </i>kick into gear tomorrow w=
hen the league=E2=80=99s board of governors approves Disney=E2=80=99s $2.6 =
billion =E2=80=9CA=E2=80=9D package, the NBC deal, and Amazon=E2=80=99s $1.=
8 billion =E2=80=9CC=E2=80=9D package. This ratification will start the clo=
ck on WBD=E2=80=99s five-day window to make a counteroffer via those matchi=
ng rights. Which, of course, isn=E2=80=99t a straightforward affair since W=
BD can=E2=80=99t actually match NBC=E2=80=99s two
primetime broadcast windows per week (Zaz and TNT Sports C.E.O. <b>Luis Sil=
berwasser</b> <i>never</i> reached out to any executives from CBS or Fox, a=
ccording to multiple sources, to explore a joint venture) or the global str=
eaming reach of Amazon=E2=80=99s Prime product. (And, some would argue, the=
 debt-strapped company shouldn=E2=80=99t be paying around $2 billion per ye=
ar for <i>anything</i>.)<br/><br/>One other fascinating road not traveled: =
Back in the spring, shortly after WBD=E2=80=99s exclusive negotiating windo=
w ended, executives with Google=E2=80=99s YouTube approached WBD to try to =
fashion a joint bid. YouTube, after all, had been in the mix to pick up the=
 package that eventually went to Amazon, and its executives wanted a way ba=
ck into the deal. Talks never got particularly serious, but they didn=E2=80=
=99t die down, either. (Of note, Zaslav and YouTube C.E.O. <b>Neal Mohan</b=
> met at Sun Valley last week. <i>Presumably</i> the NBA auction came up.) =
WBD appears certain to use its matching
rights on Amazon=E2=80=99s bid, but sources said it=E2=80=99s expected to g=
o it alone.<br/><br/>The crux of WBD=E2=80=99s pitch is that its own Max st=
reaming service, combined with its linear TV channels, should be enough to =
match Amazon=E2=80=99s streaming ambitions. Max has around 100 million worl=
dwide subscribers. Prime Video, of course, has double that amount, and it=
=E2=80=99s unlikely that the NBA will make it easy for WBD to use its match=
ing rights. NBA executives have been sitting on these deals for several wee=
ks (=E2=80=9CThey=E2=80=99re with the lawyers,=E2=80=9D has been a common r=
efrain since the spring) and essentially have moved on from TNT, its partne=
r since the 1980s, whose deal expires after next season.<br/><br/>As it wai=
ted out the NBA auction process, WBD cut several rights deals=E2=80=94the B=
ig East, French Open,  College Football Playoff, etcetera=E2=80=94and made =
moves to turn TruTV into even more of a sports channel. WBD executives insi=
st that they would have made those deals even if they=E2=80=99d won the NBA
rights. But many in the industry suspect that Zaslav and Silberwasser are s=
imply trying to save face and show that they are open for business.<br/></t=
d>
